description.text: this message file contains message for [name] package

msg.text: Unable to route from driver to the secondary spine for net $$s. Please check placement.
There is no spare H-spine available. The primary clock will be routed as a secondary clock net and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.

The driver of primary clock net $$s is not placed on one of the PIO sites dedicated for primary clocks. This primary clock will be routed to a H-spine through general routing resource or will be routed as a secondary clock and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.

All EC loads of express clock net $$s are not able to be routed as express clock due to bad placement or routing resource conflict. The unrouted EC loads will be routed through general routing resource. This net may suffer from excessive delay or skew.

Part of EC loads of express clock net $$s are not able to be routed as express clock due to bad placement or routing resource conflict. The unrouted EC loads will be routed through general routing resource. This net may suffer from excessive delay or skew.
Clock net $$s contains partial routing created in MACRO/MACO flow, clock router will unroute the existing routing in order to route it as a clock.
The clock router is unable to use the clock spine to route all clock loads on net $$s. The loads will be routed using generic routing interconnect, and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.
The clock router is unable to use the clock spine to route part of clock loads on net $$s. The loads will be routed using generic routing interconnect, and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.
The clock router is unable to find an available clock spine wire for clock net $$s. The net will be routed using generic routing interconnect, and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.
Unable to route high fanout signal.\n
Secondary clock $$s has loads or driver cross to other module, the skew cannot be guaranteed in the assembly flow.
Clock net $$s uses delayed mode. It will be routed using generic routing interconnect, and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.

A remote spine is used for the normal clock net $$s because the spine local to the driver is occupied by another net or not able to route to all/most loads through dedicated clock routing resource. This net may suffer from excessive delay or skew. You should check your preference file to see if more than one clock net is driven from the same block of four PIO cells which share a clock spine.
High-fanout net $$s uses delayed mode. It will be routed using generic routing interconnect, and may suffer from excessive delay or skew.

A remote spine is used for the high-fanout clock net $$s because the spine local to the driver is occupied by another net or not able to route to all/most loads through dedicated clock routing resource. This net may suffer from excessive delay or skew. You may need to check your preference file to see if more than one clock/hfo net is driven from the same block of four PIO cells which share a clock spine.
Clock net $$s load(s) out of the modular boundary.
Clock net $$s driver is out of the modular boundary.
Jump wire info is wrong.
Design cannot be routed due to invalid placement or locked signals.
Jumpwire (oneoutlet) across module boundary may cause routing resource conflict in the modular assemble phase.
Module width <= 1, routing resource maybe insufficient.
Module height <= 1, routing resource maybe insufficient.
Hold-time correction process will stop now due to runtime too long. To run with extra effort, read online help or run with "-exp parHold=2".
Setup time error existing in the design, AHC (Auto Hold Correction) optimization is skipped. To force hold time optimization on, please read online help or run with "-exp parHold=1".\n
Unable to do hold-time correction, check your required speed grade.\n

The hold-time optimization process will be skipped because the design currently has $$d hold-time violations, which exceeds the limits(default is $$d). To change default value, please read online help or run par with extra effort with "-exp parHold=2" \n
The hold-time violation in connection with load $$s in signal $$s is not corrected: mintarget=$$d, mindelay=$$d\n
The hold-time violation in connection from "$$s" to "$$s" in signal "$$s" is hard wired.
This kind of hold violation is not correctable. Modify your design or setting, e.g. not use IO logic.

The minimum delay target $$d ps for the connection with load $$s in signal $$s is larger than the current threshold $$d ps for a correction. This hold-time violation is not corrected. Please re-examine the design to see if the large violation can be avoided.\n

Hold-time correction will be skipped on connection with hold time violation ($$d ps),
	that is too large to correct to the default threshold ($$d ps).
	Please re-examine the design to see if the large violation can be avoided for:	signal $$s on comp $$s.
Signal $$s is a global clock which is hard-wired. The hold-time violations on this signal will be ignored.
There are $$d hold-time errors, but no connection is selected for a correction\n
scanchain length incorrect.
Signal $$s already exist on pin.
Clock is used but none of registers used on comp $$s.
The grid system has encountered problem.
Tristated net <$$s> can not be routed to busline, check bus placement on this signal.
Wire at ($$d, $$d) required for routing net <$$s> is used by another signal.
Bus wire at ($$d, $$d) required for routing net <$$s> is used by another signal.
Bus net $$s contains partial routing created in MACRO, bus router will unroute the existing routing in order to route it as a bus.
